TEXT(beginproblem());

Context("Numeric");


$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$p1 = random(2,3,1);
$p2 = random($p1+1,4,1);
$a = random(50,100,10);
$sum = $p1 + $p2;
$c = random(2,7,1);

$all_p = $sum-$c;
$ans = "($a)^($c/$all_p)";

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT

Find the exact solution to the equation below.
\[ \frac{ \log{(x^{$p1})} + \log{(x^{$p2})} }{ \log{($a x)}} = $c \]

\( x = \) \{ ans_rule(35) \}

END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

# ANS(num_cmp( $ans,tol=>0.000000000001 ) );
ANS( Compute($ans)->cmp( tolerance=>0 ) );

$cp3 = $c*$p3;
$all_pde = ( $all_p == 1 ) ? '' : "^{$all_p}";
$all_pdd = ( $all_p == 1 ) ? '' : "/$all_p";

Context()->texStrings;
SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$PAR
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$PAR
First we can multiply both sides by \( \log{($a x)} \) and get
\[ \begin{aligned}
\log{(x^{$p1})} + \log{(x^{$p2})} &= $c \ \log{($a x)} \\
\log{(x^{$p1+$p2})} &= $c \ \log{($a x)} \\
\log{(x^{$sum})} &= \log{ \left( ($a x)^{$c} \right) }
\end{aligned}\]
Now we can exponentiate both sides to get the following equation
which we solve for \(x\):
\[\begin{aligned}
x^{$sum} &= ($a x)^{$c} \\
x^{$sum} &= ($a)^{$c} x^{$c} \\
\frac{x^{$sum}}{x^{$c}} &= ($a)^{$c} \\
x^{($sum - $c)} &= ($a)^{$c} \\
x$all_pde &= ($a)^{$c},
\end{aligned}\]
so \(x = ($a)^{$c$all_pdd}\).

END_SOLUTION
